\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 One of the key philosophies behind Scrivener is that it shouldn\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92t try to force you into a particular workflow. You should be able to write any sort of long-form text in Scrivener and set up your project to fit the task at hand. Likewise, if you\u8217\'92re using Scrivener to write a novel, Scrivener doesn\u8217\'92t automatically assume that you must therefore want character sheets to fill in for each character, or prompt sheets for information about locations and so on (I apologise for the fiction-biased examples). Every writer is different\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 some novelists find filling in character sheets an essential part of their process, others dislike such things. So, just as Scrivener allows you to create top-level folders and customise their icons, it also gives you the means to set up document templates for generating things such as character sheets. Document templates allow you to set up a document in the project and use it as the basis for creating new documents.}
\par\pard\plain \fi562\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 (Note: Document templates should not be confused with project templates. A project template is something you pick from the New Project panel, which is used as the basis for creating an entire project\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 see }{\field{\*\fldinst HYPERLINK "scrivlnk://0167C3F5-F39F-4CA9-BC3E-B07F5AD11097"}{\fldrslt\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Step 21}}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 \hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 whereas a document template is a file }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1 inside}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0  a project.)}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 This probably sounds more complicated than it is in practice, so let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s take a look at how document templates appear and work in a project.}
\par\plain \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Go to the Project menu and hover over \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93New From Template\u8221\'94. When a project has document templates, they\u8217\'92re listed here so you can quickly create a new document using the template. All we see now is the placeholder menu item saying \u8220\'93No Templates Folder set\u8221\'94\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 this project doesn\u8217\'92t yet have any document templates or a folder assigned to hold them. You\u8217\'92ll see the same sub-menu if you click the down-arrow beside the green \u8220\'93Add\u8221\'94 button in the toolbar and check the \u8220\'93New From Template\u8221\'94 menu there.}
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0  Let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s create a couple of document templates to populate these menus. For this step, you may want to split the editor so you can follow along while keeping this reference up to the side. (Remember, selecting a document in the binder will load it in the editor with the blue header. You may need to click into the editor you want to change before following steps to click in the binder. To avoid accidentally replacing this document, choose \u8220\'93Lock In Place\u8221\'94 from the icon menu in this split\u8217\'92s header.)}
\par\pard\plain \tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl360\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs30\b0\i1\ul\ulc0 Setting Up Document Templates}
\par\pard\plain \ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Take a look inside the Research folder in the binder (expand it if necessary by clicking on the disclosure triangle next to it). Inside it you will find a \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Sheets\u8221\'94 folder, which contains two documents\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 \u8220\'93Character Sheet\u8221\'94 and \u8220\'93Location Sheet\u8221\'94. Take a look at these documents. They contain text that could be used for very basic character or location sheets, which you might fill in for each character or location you are going to write about in a novel. They are just regular text documents, though\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 you can have whatever you want in there. To see what I mean, select the \u8220\'93Location\u8221\'94 document and then click on \u8220\'93Add\u8221\'94 in the toolbar so that a new blank document gets created. Name it to anything you want, and then type something inside the document.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1040\fi562\sa120\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Now we\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92re going to tell Scrivener that the documents inside the \u8220\'93Sheets\u8221\'94 folder should be treated as document templates\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 that is, that we want to be able to create new documents based on them:}
\par\pard\plain \li850\fi561\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	1.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Click on the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Sheets\u8221\'94 folder to select it.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	2.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Go to the Project menu and choose \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Set Selection as Templates Folder\u8221\'94.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1040\fi561\sa200\sb200\qc\ltrch\loch {\*\shppict{\pict{\*\nisusfilename Clipboard Image}\picw146\pich72\picwgoal2910\pichgoal1440\pngblip }}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 \line }{\f2\fs22\b0\i1 After turning the \loch\af2\hich\af2\dbch\af2\uc1\u8220\'93Sheets\u8221\'94 folder into a Document Template folder.}
\par\pard\plain \tx1040\fi562\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 The icon of the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Sheets\u8221\'94 folder will change to be a white \u8220\'93T\u8221\'94 against a blueprint, and the \u8220\'93T\u8221\'94 will appear in the corner of each document inside the folder. This indicates that the folder is now acting as the templates folder and that anything inside it can be used as the basis for a new document. (Note that once you have set a templates folder, the \u8220\'93Set Selection as Templates Folder\u8221\'94 item in the Project menu will change to \u8220\'93Clear Templates Folder\u8221\'94. Since each project can only have one templates folder, if you want to change the templates folder in the future, you will need to use this to reset things before \u8220\'93Set Selection as Templates Folder\u8221\'94 becomes available again.)}
\par\pard\plain \tx560\tx1120\tx1680\tx2240\tx2800\tx3360\tx3920\tx4480\tx5040\tx5600\tx6160\tx6720\sl360\slmult1\ql\ltrch\loch {\f2\fs30\b0\i1\ul\ulc0 Using Document Templates}
\par\pard\plain \tx1040\sa120\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 What does this mean? Let\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s try returning to the menus we looked at a little earlier:}
\par\pard\plain \li850\fi561\ltrch\loch \ls2\ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	1.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Click on the \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Characters\u8221\'94 folder with the custom icon that you created in step 19. It should currently be empty.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	2.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Go to the Project menu and select \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93New From Template\u8221\'94 again. You\u8217\'92ll notice that it\u8217\'92s no longer empty\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 it shows the contents of the \u8220\'93Sheets\u8221\'94 templates folder.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	3.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 From the menu, select \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Character Sheet\u8221\'94. A new document will be created inside the \u8220\'93Characters\u8221\'94 folder\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 a document that is identical to the \u8220\'93Character Sheet\u8221\'94 document in the templates folder. Change the title and edit the text in the document itself.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext\f1\fs26\b0\i0	4.	}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0 Now click on the down-arrow beside the green \loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8220\'93Add\u8221\'94 button again. This time there will be more items in the sub-menu\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 the contents of our templates folder is there, too. Select the item you created previously. You should see the text you typed in appear in the editor. Anything you had done to this item beforehand would have been copied over (excluding snapshots, so you can store copies of older versions of your templates without them getting in the way).}
\par\pard\plain \tx1040\fi562\sb120\ql\ltrch\loch {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 The two new documents you just created are }{\f2\fs26\b0\i1 copies}{\f1\fs26\b0\i0  of the documents in the templates folder. And that\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92s really all the templates folder is\hich\f1 \emdash \loch\f1 somewhere for you to put documents that you want to use as the basis for other documents, and which, in combination with the New From Template menu, makes it very easy to create copies of those documents anywhere you want in the project.}
\par\pard\plain \fi562\ltrch\loch \f1\fs26\b0\i0\cf1
\par\plain {\f1\fs26\b0\i0 We\loch\af1\hich\af1\dbch\af1\uc1\u8217\'92re nearly there. If you split the editor, go ahead and close it now, and unlock this editor if needed. Then on to Step 21\u8230\'85}}